qed-claim-3.quantum-electrodynamics.matr.statement: matrix elements for complex processes in electrodynamics can be written down directly using a space-time approach, providing considerable simplification over conventional methods

qed-claim-4.quantum-electrodynamics.the.statement: the space-time view makes relativistic invariance self-evident, in contrast to the hamiltonian method which obscures it

qed-claim-5.quantum-electrodynamics.each.statement: each term in the expansion in powers of e²/ℏc can be written down and understood directly from a physical point of view

ren-claim-2.renormalization.by modifying.statement: by modifying the interaction of electrons at short distances, all matrix elements become finite except those relating to vacuum polarization

ren-claim-3.renormalization.the only eff.statement: the only effects sensitive to the modification are changes in mass and charge of electrons, which cannot be directly observed

ren-claim-4.renormalization.phenomena di.statement: phenomena directly observable are insensitive to the details of the modification used (except at extreme energies), allowing a limit to be taken as the range of modification goes to zero

fd-claim-2.feynman-diagrams.the simplifi.statement: the simplification results from combining processes that were previously unnecessarily separated, such as processes involving virtual pairs with those involving only positive energy electrons

fd-claim-3.feynman-diagrams.the space-ti.statement: the space-time approach permits matrix elements to be written down directly for any specific problem without requiring the complicated machinery of hamiltonian electrodynamics

qed-postulate-2.quantum-electrodynamics..statement: electrodynamics can be described as a direct interaction at a distance (albeit delayed in time) between charges, rather than through field oscillators

qed-postulate-3.quantum-electrodynamics..statement: the interaction viewpoint is best for virtual quanta, while the field viewpoint is best for real quanta

qed-assumption-3.quantum-electrodynamics.statement: the interaction between charges can be modified at short distances to make divergent integrals finite
qed-assumption-3.quantum-electrodynamics.rationale: this modification allows systematic removal of infinities through renormalization

qed-assumption-4.quantum-electrodynamics.statement: observable phenomena are insensitive to the details of the short-distance modification (except at extreme energies)
qed-assumption-4.quantum-electrodynamics.rationale: this allows taking the limit as the cut-off goes to zero for observable processes
